Note:
MIPS Instruction Encoder - Binary Machine Code Encoding

This file encodes MIPS instructions into their 32-bit binary representations
according to the MIPS32 instruction set architecture. All MIPS instructions
are exactly 32 bits (4 bytes) wide, encoded in one of three formats:

  R-format: |opcode(6)|rs(5)|rt(5)|rd(5)|shamt(5)|funct(6)|
  I-format: |opcode(6)|rs(5)|rt(5)|immediate(16)|
  J-format: |opcode(6)|target(26)|

This file performs the following tasks:
- Encode R-format instructions (ADD, SUB, AND, OR, XOR, SLT, JR, MULT, DIV, etc.)
- Encode I-format instructions (ADDI, LW, SW, BEQ, BNE, LUI, ORI, ANDI, etc.)
- Encode J-format instructions (J, JAL)
- Encode special instructions (SYSCALL, BREAK, NOP, MFHI, MFLO)
- Handle branch delay slot NOP insertion
- Validate instruction fields against bit-width constraints

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Direct binary encoding produces correct MIPS machine code for execution
- Correct field placement in each format is critical for hardware decoding
- Branch delay slot handling is required for correct MIPS execution semantics
- Field validation prevents silent corruption from out-of-range operands

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- R-format, I-format, and J-format encoding functions
- Per-instruction encoders for common ALU, memory, branch, and jump operations
- Delay slot NOP emission for branches and jumps
- Field validation and encoding error detection

Dependencies:
- Imports Layout for output buffer allocation
- Imports List for instruction buffer management
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MIPS OPCODE AND FUNCTION CODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
MIPS R-format instructions use opcode 0x00 (SPECIAL) with the operation
selected by the 6-bit function code. I-format and J-format instructions
use non-zero opcodes to identify the operation directly.

All constants are decimal representations of the standard MIPS32 encoding values.
@End Reasoning

Note: R-format: opcode field is 0x00 (SPECIAL), operation selected by funct field
Constant MIPS_OP_SPECIAL as Integer is 0   Note: 0x00 minus R-format group

Note: R-format function codes (funct field, bits 5:0)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SLL as Integer is 0    Note: 0x00 minus Shift Left Logical
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SRL as Integer is 2    Note: 0x02 minus Shift Right Logical
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SRA as Integer is 3    Note: 0x03 minus Shift Right Arithmetic
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SLLV as Integer is 4   Note: 0x04 minus Shift Left Logical Variable
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SRLV as Integer is 6   Note: 0x06 minus Shift Right Logical Variable
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SRAV as Integer is 7   Note: 0x07 minus Shift Right Arithmetic Variable
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_JR as Integer is 8     Note: 0x08 minus Jump Register
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_JALR as Integer is 9   Note: 0x09 minus Jump And Link Register
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SYSCALL as Integer is 12 Note: 0x0C minus System Call
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_BREAK as Integer is 13   Note: 0x0D minus Breakpoint
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_MFHI as Integer is 16  Note: 0x10 minus Move From HI
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_MTHI as Integer is 17  Note: 0x11 minus Move To HI
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_MFLO as Integer is 18  Note: 0x12 minus Move From LO
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_MTLO as Integer is 19  Note: 0x13 minus Move To LO
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_MULT as Integer is 24  Note: 0x18 minus Multiply (signed)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_MULTU as Integer is 25 Note: 0x19 minus Multiply (unsigned)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_DIV as Integer is 26   Note: 0x1A minus Divide (signed)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_DIVU as Integer is 27  Note: 0x1B minus Divide (unsigned)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_ADD as Integer is 32   Note: 0x20 minus Add (with overflow trap)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_ADDU as Integer is 33  Note: 0x21 minus Add Unsigned (no trap)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SUB as Integer is 34   Note: 0x22 minus Subtract (with overflow trap)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SUBU as Integer is 35  Note: 0x23 minus Subtract Unsigned (no trap)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_AND as Integer is 36   Note: 0x24 minus Bitwise AND
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_OR as Integer is 37    Note: 0x25 minus Bitwise OR
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_XOR as Integer is 38   Note: 0x26 minus Bitwise XOR
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_NOR as Integer is 39   Note: 0x27 minus Bitwise NOR
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SLT as Integer is 42   Note: 0x2A minus Set on Less Than (signed)
Constant MIPS_FUNCT_SLTU as Integer is 43  Note: 0x2B minus Set on Less Than Unsigned

Note: I-format opcodes
Constant MIPS_OP_BEQ as Integer is 4       Note: 0x04 minus Branch on Equal
Constant MIPS_OP_BNE as Integer is 5       Note: 0x05 minus Branch on Not Equal
Constant MIPS_OP_BLEZ as Integer is 6      Note: 0x06 minus Branch on Less Than or Equal to Zero
Constant MIPS_OP_BGTZ as Integer is 7      Note: 0x07 minus Branch on Greater Than Zero
Constant MIPS_OP_ADDI as Integer is 8      Note: 0x08 minus Add Immediate (with overflow)
Constant MIPS_OP_ADDIU as Integer is 9     Note: 0x09 minus Add Immediate Unsigned
Constant MIPS_OP_SLTI as Integer is 10     Note: 0x0A minus Set on Less Than Immediate
Constant MIPS_OP_SLTIU as Integer is 11    Note: 0x0B minus Set on Less Than Immediate Unsigned
Constant MIPS_OP_ANDI as Integer is 12     Note: 0x0C minus AND Immediate
Constant MIPS_OP_ORI as Integer is 13      Note: 0x0D minus OR Immediate
Constant MIPS_OP_XORI as Integer is 14     Note: 0x0E minus XOR Immediate
Constant MIPS_OP_LUI as Integer is 15      Note: 0x0F minus Load Upper Immediate
Constant MIPS_OP_LB as Integer is 32       Note: 0x20 minus Load Byte
Constant MIPS_OP_LH as Integer is 33       Note: 0x21 minus Load Halfword
Constant MIPS_OP_LW as Integer is 35       Note: 0x23 minus Load Word
Constant MIPS_OP_LBU as Integer is 36      Note: 0x24 minus Load Byte Unsigned
Constant MIPS_OP_LHU as Integer is 37      Note: 0x25 minus Load Halfword Unsigned
Constant MIPS_OP_SB as Integer is 40       Note: 0x28 minus Store Byte
Constant MIPS_OP_SH as Integer is 41       Note: 0x29 minus Store Halfword
Constant MIPS_OP_SW as Integer is 43       Note: 0x2B minus Store Word

Note: J-format opcodes
Constant MIPS_OP_J as Integer is 2         Note: 0x02 minus Jump
Constant MIPS_OP_JAL as Integer is 3       Note: 0x03 minus Jump And Link

Note: REGIMM opcodes (opcode 0x01, operation in rt field)
Constant MIPS_OP_REGIMM as Integer is 1    Note: 0x01 minus REGIMM group
Constant MIPS_RT_BLTZ as Integer is 0      Note: 0x00 minus Branch on Less Than Zero
Constant MIPS_RT_BGEZ as Integer is 1      Note: 0x01 minus Branch on Greater Than or Equal to Zero

Note: NOP encoding (SLL $zero, $zero, 0)
Constant MIPS_NOP as Integer is 0          Note: 0x00000000

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BIT MANIPULATION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "mask_bits" that takes value as Integer, bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Masks a value to the specified number of low bits. For example,
    mask_bits(value, 5) returns value AND 0x1F (low 5 bits).
    This is used to ensure instruction fields do not exceed their bit widths.

    Implementation: compute 2^bits - 1 as the mask, then AND with value.
    For negative values (sign-extended immediates), this correctly truncates
    to the field width.
    @End Reasoning

    Let mask be 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than bits:
        Set mask to mask multiplied by 2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Set mask to mask minus 1

    Note: Handle negative values by converting to their unsigned representation
    If value is less than 0:
        Note: For a signed immediate that needs to be truncated to N bits,
        Note: we compute the two's complement representation within the field
        Let adjusted be value plus mask plus 1
        Return adjusted minus ((adjusted divided by (mask plus 1)) multiplied by (mask plus 1))
    End If

    Return value minus ((value divided by (mask plus 1)) multiplied by (mask plus 1))
End Process

Process called "shift_left" that takes value as Integer, amount as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Shifts a value left by the specified number of bits. Equivalent to
    value shifted left by amount. Implemented as repeated multiplication by 2.
    @End Reasoning

    Let result be value
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than amount:
        Set result to result multiplied by 2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FORMAT ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_r_type" that takes opcode as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer, rd as Integer, shamt as Integer, funct as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes an R-format MIPS instruction into a 32-bit word.
    Layout: |opcode(6)|rs(5)|rt(5)|rd(5)|shamt(5)|funct(6)|

    Bit positions (MSB to LSB):
      opcode: bits 31-26
      rs:     bits 25-21
      rt:     bits 20-16
      rd:     bits 15-11
      shamt:  bits 10-6
      funct:  bits 5-0

    All fields are masked to their bit widths to prevent overflow.
    @End Reasoning

    Let encoded be 0
    Set encoded to shift_left(mask_bits(opcode, 6), 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rs, 5), 21)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rt, 5), 16)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rd, 5), 11)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(shamt, 5), 6)
    Set encoded to encoded plus mask_bits(funct, 6)
    Return encoded
End Process

Process called "encode_i_type" that takes opcode as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes an I-format MIPS instruction into a 32-bit word.
    Layout: |opcode(6)|rs(5)|rt(5)|immediate(16)|

    Bit positions:
      opcode:    bits 31-26
      rs:        bits 25-21
      rt:        bits 20-16
      immediate: bits 15-0

    The immediate field is signed for arithmetic and branch instructions
    but unsigned for logical instructions (ANDI, ORI, XORI). The caller
    is responsible for sign semantics; this function only places the
    low 16 bits.
    @End Reasoning

    Let encoded be 0
    Set encoded to shift_left(mask_bits(opcode, 6), 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rs, 5), 21)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rt, 5), 16)
    Set encoded to encoded plus mask_bits(immediate, 16)
    Return encoded
End Process

Process called "encode_j_type" that takes opcode as Integer, target as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes a J-format MIPS instruction into a 32-bit word.
    Layout: |opcode(6)|target(26)|

    Bit positions:
      opcode: bits 31-26
      target: bits 25-0

    The target field holds the word-aligned address shifted right by 2 bits.
    The full jump target is formed by:
      PC[31:28] | target[25:0] shifted left by 2
    This gives a 256 MB jump range within the current 256 MB region.
    @End Reasoning

    Let encoded be shift_left(mask_bits(opcode, 6), 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus mask_bits(target, 26)
    Return encoded
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: R-FORMAT INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_add" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ADD rd, rs, rt - rd = rs + rt (overflow trap)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_ADD)
End Process

Process called "encode_addu" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ADDU rd, rs, rt - rd = rs + rt (no overflow trap)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_ADDU)
End Process

Process called "encode_sub" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SUB rd, rs, rt - rd = rs - rt (overflow trap)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_SUB)
End Process

Process called "encode_subu" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SUBU rd, rs, rt - rd = rs - rt (no overflow trap)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_SUBU)
End Process

Process called "encode_and" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: AND rd, rs, rt - rd = rs AND rt
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_AND)
End Process

Process called "encode_or" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: OR rd, rs, rt - rd = rs OR rt
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_OR)
End Process

Process called "encode_xor" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: XOR rd, rs, rt - rd = rs XOR rt
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_XOR)
End Process

Process called "encode_nor" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NOR rd, rs, rt - rd = NOT(rs OR rt)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_NOR)
End Process

Process called "encode_slt" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SLT rd, rs, rt - rd = (rs < rt) ? 1 : 0 (signed)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_SLT)
End Process

Process called "encode_sltu" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SLTU rd, rs, rt - rd = (rs < rt) ? 1 : 0 (unsigned)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_SLTU)
End Process

Process called "encode_sll" that takes rd as Integer, rt as Integer, shamt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SLL rd, rt, shamt - rd = rt shifted left by shamt
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, 0, rt, rd, shamt, MIPS_FUNCT_SLL)
End Process

Process called "encode_srl" that takes rd as Integer, rt as Integer, shamt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SRL rd, rt, shamt - rd = rt shifted right by shamt (logical)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, 0, rt, rd, shamt, MIPS_FUNCT_SRL)
End Process

Process called "encode_sra" that takes rd as Integer, rt as Integer, shamt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SRA rd, rt, shamt - rd = rt shifted right by shamt (arithmetic)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, 0, rt, rd, shamt, MIPS_FUNCT_SRA)
End Process

Process called "encode_sllv" that takes rd as Integer, rt as Integer, rs as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SLLV rd, rt, rs - rd = rt shifted left by rs[4:0]
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_SLLV)
End Process

Process called "encode_srlv" that takes rd as Integer, rt as Integer, rs as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SRLV rd, rt, rs - rd = rt shifted right by rs[4:0] (logical)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_SRLV)
End Process

Process called "encode_srav" that takes rd as Integer, rt as Integer, rs as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SRAV rd, rt, rs - rd = rt shifted right by rs[4:0] (arithmetic)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_SRAV)
End Process

Process called "encode_mult" that takes rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MULT rs, rt - {HI, LO} = rs * rt (signed)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, 0, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_MULT)
End Process

Process called "encode_multu" that takes rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MULTU rs, rt - {HI, LO} = rs * rt (unsigned)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, 0, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_MULTU)
End Process

Process called "encode_div" that takes rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: DIV rs, rt - LO = rs / rt, HI = rs % rt (signed)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, 0, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_DIV)
End Process

Process called "encode_divu" that takes rs as Integer, rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: DIVU rs, rt - LO = rs / rt, HI = rs % rt (unsigned)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, rt, 0, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_DIVU)
End Process

Process called "encode_mfhi" that takes rd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MFHI rd - rd = HI
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, 0, 0, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_MFHI)
End Process

Process called "encode_mflo" that takes rd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MFLO rd - rd = LO
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, 0, 0, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_MFLO)
End Process

Process called "encode_mthi" that takes rs as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MTHI rs - HI = rs
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, 0, 0, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_MTHI)
End Process

Process called "encode_mtlo" that takes rs as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MTLO rs - LO = rs
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, 0, 0, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_MTLO)
End Process

Process called "encode_jr" that takes rs as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: JR rs - PC = rs (jump to register)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, 0, 0, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_JR)
End Process

Process called "encode_jalr" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: JALR rd, rs - rd = PC+8, PC = rs (jump and link register)
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, rs, 0, rd, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_JALR)
End Process

Process called "encode_syscall" returns Integer:
    Note: SYSCALL - transfer control to OS kernel
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, 0, 0, 0, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_SYSCALL)
End Process

Process called "encode_break" returns Integer:
    Note: BREAK - breakpoint exception
    Return encode_r_type(MIPS_OP_SPECIAL, 0, 0, 0, 0, MIPS_FUNCT_BREAK)
End Process

Process called "encode_nop" returns Integer:
    Note: NOP is encoded as SLL $zero, $zero, 0 = 0x00000000
    Return MIPS_NOP
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: I-FORMAT INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_addiu" that takes rt as Integer, rs as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ADDIU rt, rs, immediate - rt = rs + sign_extend(immediate)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_ADDIU, rs, rt, immediate)
End Process

Process called "encode_addi" that takes rt as Integer, rs as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ADDI rt, rs, immediate - rt = rs + sign_extend(immediate), trap on overflow
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_ADDI, rs, rt, immediate)
End Process

Process called "encode_andi" that takes rt as Integer, rs as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ANDI rt, rs, immediate - rt = rs AND zero_extend(immediate)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_ANDI, rs, rt, immediate)
End Process

Process called "encode_ori" that takes rt as Integer, rs as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ORI rt, rs, immediate - rt = rs OR zero_extend(immediate)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_ORI, rs, rt, immediate)
End Process

Process called "encode_xori" that takes rt as Integer, rs as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: XORI rt, rs, immediate - rt = rs XOR zero_extend(immediate)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_XORI, rs, rt, immediate)
End Process

Process called "encode_slti" that takes rt as Integer, rs as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SLTI rt, rs, immediate - rt = (rs < sign_extend(immediate)) ? 1 : 0
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_SLTI, rs, rt, immediate)
End Process

Process called "encode_sltiu" that takes rt as Integer, rs as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SLTIU rt, rs, immediate - rt = (rs < sign_extend(immediate)) ? 1 : 0 (unsigned)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_SLTIU, rs, rt, immediate)
End Process

Process called "encode_lui" that takes rt as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LUI rt, immediate - rt = immediate shifted left by 16
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_LUI, 0, rt, immediate)
End Process

Process called "encode_lw" that takes rt as Integer, offset as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LW rt, offset(base) - rt = memory[base + sign_extend(offset)]
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_LW, base, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_lh" that takes rt as Integer, offset as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LH rt, offset(base) - rt = sign_extend(halfword at base + offset)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_LH, base, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_lhu" that takes rt as Integer, offset as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LHU rt, offset(base) - rt = zero_extend(halfword at base + offset)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_LHU, base, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_lb" that takes rt as Integer, offset as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LB rt, offset(base) - rt = sign_extend(byte at base + offset)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_LB, base, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_lbu" that takes rt as Integer, offset as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LBU rt, offset(base) - rt = zero_extend(byte at base + offset)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_LBU, base, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_sw" that takes rt as Integer, offset as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SW rt, offset(base) - memory[base + sign_extend(offset)] = rt
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_SW, base, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_sh" that takes rt as Integer, offset as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SH rt, offset(base) - store halfword
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_SH, base, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_sb" that takes rt as Integer, offset as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SB rt, offset(base) - store byte
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_SB, base, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_beq" that takes rs as Integer, rt as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    BEQ rs, rt, offset - branch if rs == rt.
    The offset is a signed 16-bit value representing the number of instructions
    (not bytes) from the instruction following the branch (PC+4). The hardware
    computes: target = (PC+4) + (sign_extend(offset) shifted left by 2).
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_BEQ, rs, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_bne" that takes rs as Integer, rt as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BNE rs, rt, offset - branch if rs != rt
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_BNE, rs, rt, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_blez" that takes rs as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BLEZ rs, offset - branch if rs <= 0
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_BLEZ, rs, 0, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_bgtz" that takes rs as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BGTZ rs, offset - branch if rs > 0
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_BGTZ, rs, 0, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_bltz" that takes rs as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BLTZ rs, offset - branch if rs < 0 (uses REGIMM opcode)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_REGIMM, rs, MIPS_RT_BLTZ, offset)
End Process

Process called "encode_bgez" that takes rs as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BGEZ rs, offset - branch if rs >= 0 (uses REGIMM opcode)
    Return encode_i_type(MIPS_OP_REGIMM, rs, MIPS_RT_BGEZ, offset)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: J-FORMAT INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_j" that takes target_addr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    J target - unconditional jump. The target address is a 26-bit word-aligned
    address. The actual target is formed by:
      (PC+4)[31:28] | target[25:0] shifted left by 2
    The caller must shift the byte address right by 2 before passing it.
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_j_type(MIPS_OP_J, target_addr)
End Process

Process called "encode_jal" that takes target_addr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    JAL target - jump and link (function call). Saves return address in $ra ($31).
    $ra = PC + 8 (address of instruction after the delay slot).
    Target formation is the same as J.
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_j_type(MIPS_OP_JAL, target_addr)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INSTRUCTION EMISSION TO OUTPUT BUFFER
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "emit_instruction" that takes output as Integer, instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a single 32-bit MIPS instruction to the output buffer in big-endian
    byte order (MIPS is typically big-endian, though MIPS can be either).
    The instruction is decomposed into 4 bytes and written sequentially.

    Byte order (big-endian):
      byte 0: bits 31-24 (most significant)
      byte 1: bits 23-16
      byte 2: bits 15-8
      byte 3: bits 7-0  (least significant)
    @End Reasoning

    Let byte0 be instruction divided by 16777216          Note: shifted right by 24
    Let byte1 be (instruction divided by 65536) minus (byte0 multiplied by 256)  Note: shifted right by 16 bitwise and 0xFF
    Let remainder be instruction minus (byte0 multiplied by 16777216) minus (byte1 multiplied by 65536)
    Let byte2 be remainder divided by 256                  Note: shifted right by 8
    Let byte3 be remainder minus (byte2 multiplied by 256)        Note: bitwise and 0xFF

    Set byte0 to mask_bits(byte0, 8)
    Set byte1 to mask_bits(byte1, 8)
    Set byte2 to mask_bits(byte2, 8)
    Set byte3 to mask_bits(byte3, 8)

    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte0)
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte1)
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte2)
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte3)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "emit_instruction_le" that takes output as Integer, instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a single 32-bit MIPS instruction in little-endian byte order.
    Used for MIPSEL (little-endian MIPS) targets such as many embedded
    systems and some Android devices.
    @End Reasoning

    Let byte0 be instruction divided by 16777216
    Let byte1 be (instruction divided by 65536) minus (byte0 multiplied by 256)
    Let remainder be instruction minus (byte0 multiplied by 16777216) minus (byte1 multiplied by 65536)
    Let byte2 be remainder divided by 256
    Let byte3 be remainder minus (byte2 multiplied by 256)

    Set byte0 to mask_bits(byte0, 8)
    Set byte1 to mask_bits(byte1, 8)
    Set byte2 to mask_bits(byte2, 8)
    Set byte3 to mask_bits(byte3, 8)

    Note: Little-endian: least significant byte first
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte3)
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte2)
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte1)
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte0)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "emit_nop" that takes output as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits a NOP instruction. Used for branch delay slots and alignment padding.
    NOP on MIPS is SLL $zero, $zero, 0 = 0x00000000.
    @End Reasoning
    Return emit_instruction(output, MIPS_NOP)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BRANCH DELAY SLOT HANDLING
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "emit_branch_with_delay" that takes output as Integer, branch_instr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits a branch instruction followed by a NOP in the delay slot. MIPS
    executes the instruction in the delay slot (the instruction immediately
    after a branch/jump) regardless of whether the branch is taken. A NOP
    is the safe default when no useful instruction can fill the delay slot.
    @End Reasoning

    Let result be emit_instruction(output, branch_instr)
    If result equals 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return emit_nop(output)
End Process

Process called "emit_jump_with_delay" that takes output as Integer, jump_instr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits a jump instruction followed by a NOP in the delay slot.
    Same delay slot behavior as branches.
    @End Reasoning

    Let result be emit_instruction(output, jump_instr)
    If result equals 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return emit_nop(output)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PSEUDO-INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_li" that takes output as Integer, rt as Integer, immediate as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes the LI (Load Immediate) pseudo-instruction. This loads a 32-bit
    constant into a register. Depending on the value:

    - If value fits in 16 bits signed (-32768 to 32767):
      Single instruction: ADDIU rt, $zero, immediate

    - If value fits in upper 16 bits only (low 16 bits are zero):
      Single instruction: LUI rt, upper16

    - Otherwise requires two instructions:
      LUI rt, upper16
      ORI rt, rt, lower16
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check if value fits in 16-bit signed range
    If immediate is greater than or equal to -32768:
        If immediate is less than or equal to 32767:
            Let instr be encode_addiu(rt, 0, immediate)
            Return emit_instruction(output, instr)
        End If
    End If

    Note: Split into upper and lower 16 bits
    Let upper16 be immediate divided by 65536
    Let lower16 be immediate minus (upper16 multiplied by 65536)

    Note: Handle negative values
    If immediate is less than 0:
        Note: For negative values, adjust upper half
        If lower16 is less than 0:
            Set lower16 to lower16 plus 65536
            Set upper16 to upper16 minus 1
        End If
    End If

    Set upper16 to mask_bits(upper16, 16)
    Set lower16 to mask_bits(lower16, 16)

    Note: Check if lower 16 bits are zero (LUI only needed)
    If lower16 equals 0:
        Set instr to encode_lui(rt, upper16)
        Return emit_instruction(output, instr)
    End If

    Note: Full 32-bit load: LUI + ORI
    Let lui_instr be encode_lui(rt, upper16)
    emit_instruction(output, lui_instr)
    Let ori_instr be encode_ori(rt, rt, lower16)
    Return emit_instruction(output, ori_instr)
End Process

Process called "encode_la" that takes output as Integer, rt as Integer, address as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes the LA (Load Address) pseudo-instruction. Loads a 32-bit address
    into a register. Semantically equivalent to LI for immediate addresses.
    For PIC code, this would use GP-relative addressing, but for static
    linking we use the LUI+ORI pair.
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_li(output, rt, address)
End Process

Process called "encode_move" that takes rd as Integer, rs as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes the MOVE pseudo-instruction as ADDU rd, rs, $zero.
    MOVE rd, rs copies the value of rs into rd.
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_addu(rd, rs, 0)
End Process
